What we are facing today is an unprecedented event in history. We remained isolated, confined to our homes however our lives continued, even during the standstill. We started paying attention to little things - the blossoming of flowers, clear or grey skies, variety of birds flying around us, sometimes eerily silent roads or beaches depending on where we were. A lot changed and a lot began to be noticed! 
 
Many around the world picked up their cameras to document some of these small, seemingly insignificant or significant moments of everyday life under lockdown. 
 
At this instance, Aditya Arya, Founder Director of India Photo Archive Foundation, Museo Camera and Dahuez began the #LockDownDiaries to gather some of these images, a sort of a journal of these special times. In the words of Aditya, ‘Photographers are visual historians who are creating visual stories which future academicians are going to use as important source material”. 
 
Curated by a jury of eminent photographers, Photo Exhibition – The Lockdown Diaries, a visual journal of life under lockdown is now on display at Museo Camera, DLF Phase – 4, Gurgaon. The exhibition is showcasing works of over 50 photographers & enthusiasts, documenting life under lockdown. Make time to visit if you can & Stay Safe!

Since I was able to finish some work today, I decided to clean up my room. I also tidy up my entire plastic model collection. I now have a sizable PlaMo wall. I now have a total of 130 kits counting the add ons(65 Bandai and Kotobukiya kits, 65 Bootleg kits). As much as I want to use this as my background for my online classes, my parents thought it wouldn't send a good message to anyone who'd see. So I had to clean them up and set up an angle of my room where they would see my small bookshelf instead of my boxes. I strongly believe this would show that I'm doing my own art that is different from my writing. I believe that PlaMo building in itself is a form of art and performance. I know I'm not doing any recolors or drastic color change on my kits but I'm getting there. I'd just have to invest on a small compressor and airbrush set and I'll be ready. I've been planning to do so but some things don't always go your way. Still, this clean up allowed me to look into my hobby not just as a hobby but a lifestyle; something that you have to invest time and resources in order to be good at. Salute to my fellow builders out there! 
For now, allow me to put these boxes back.

node.text: CefaluÃÄ. If you have to pick from the many gems of Sicily, make sure CefaluÃÄ is one of them. The town first finds mention in 360 BC. node.text:
“All freedom is relative — you know too well — and sometimes it’s no freedom at all, but simply the cage widening far away from you, the bars abstracted with distance but still there, as when they “free” wild animals into nature preserves only to contain them yet again by larger borders.”

On earth we’re briefly gorgeous by @ocean_vuong is my favourite book of 2020. This couldn’t have been fiction, for the rawness of characters, experiences, the wallops of sensibilities, dubious repentance, felt like a documented re-telling of a livid, lived episode. 

This is a letter from a son to his mother, content of which is written with a hope to be read someday, understood someday, felt someday. His family is a survivor of the war in Vietnam, distorted fragments of which is seen in what follows their survival. For a story this short, the topics branched bears quite some weight.

Ocean Vuong explores language on both a micro and macro level. A sense of poetry flows down in the writing (not surprising considering Ocean Voung is widely popular for his poems!), streaming across subjects of sexuality, race, gender, masculinity, grief and language. 

Please give this a read. This is simple beauty of words, fear and ache, memory and survival, existence. 

Current goodreads rating: 4.05, and a delightful 10 for me! üíï

#ICANPROTECT Fashion Campaign 

The New Normal is definitely not a trend, and the presence of COVID-19 is undoubtedly unfashionable. This pandemic devastated many industries including the realm of fashion, but we say no to a curtain call. Many fashion designers, fashion entrepreneurs and everyone involved in this industry deviated from their usual jobs and devised other ways to make ends meet and sustain their livelihood. Despite a dire situation, benevolent hearts within the fashion circle lent a helping hand by organizing donation drives for the less privileged communities and created protective suits and facemasks for our frontliners. 
In support to this industry, I will promote businesses, encourage consumers, patronize services and participate in advocacies of protecting and saving lives. Being essential will always be fashionable and I AM ESSENTIAL in protecting this industry. I CAN PROTECT one's sustenance, I am #ProFashion and #ProLife. Let us all be empowered to help and inspire so we can survive and thrive while we wait for better days to come.
